Isolation Comments: isolated at the University of Maryland Hospital
Comments: Escherichia coli strain CFT073. This strain (CFT073; O6:K2:H1) is uropathogenic E. coli (UPEC) one of the most common causes of non-hospital-acquired urinary tract infections. There are numerous important differences between EHEC and UPEC, namely the loss of specific virulence factors such as the type III secretion system and plasmid- and phage-associated PAIs. UPEC has gained fimbrial operons, including genes for production of Pap pili, as well as other virulence factors that allow it to colonize the urinary tract.

Isolation Comments: isolated from an American soldier who had diarrhea in Viet Nam
Comments: Escherichia coli strain B7A . This enterotoxigenic (ETEC) strain (O148:H28:CS6:LT+:ST+) was isolated from an American soldier who had diarrhea in Viet Nam. ETEC strains cause traveler's diarrhea which is characterized by a large volume of water diarrhea. This strain colonizes the small intestine via pili, and two toxins, heat-stable enterotoxin (ST+) and heat-labile enterotoxin (LT+), are responsible for the virulence. Additional pathogenicity factors include the serotype O148:H28, and CFA (colonization factor antigen) type CS6 (coli surface antigen 6). Virulence has been confirmed in humans. This strain contains multiple plasmids and was obtained from Maj. Carl Brinkley at Walter Reed Army Institute of Research.The stock used for genomic DNA preparation was obtained from a master- and production-cGMP cell bank available at WRAIR/NMRC. Genomic sequencing included two libraries: a small insert library (4-5 kb) and a large insert library (10-12 kb) from which 19,970 and 45,144 reads were sequenced, respectively.  This amount of sequence represents 10X coverage of the genome. The preliminary assembly is composed of 198 contigs.

Isolation Comments: isolated from an oubreak of diarrhea in 1987 in Finland that affected 650 students and was spread in a person-to-person manner which is unusual for enteropathogenic Escherichia coli (EPEC)
Comments: Escherichia coli strain E110019. This strain (E110019; serotype O111:H9) was isolated from an oubreak of diarrhea in 1987 in Finland that affected 650 students and was spread in a person-to-person manner which is unusual for enteropathogenic Escherichia coli (EPEC). Therefore, this strain represents an atypical EPEC strain and it does not contain previously identified EPEC virulence factors such as the EAF plasmid. It represents a shift in the predominant group of EPEC pathogens causing disease in the industrialized world.Genomic sequencing included two libraries: a small insert library (4-5 kb) and a large insert library (10-12 kb) from which 22,506 and 45,129 reads were sequenced, respectively.  This amount of sequence represents 10 X coverage of the genome. The preliminary project assembly contains 115 contigs.

Isolation Comments: isolated from a woman with a case of cystitis (infection of the bladder with no involvement of kidneys or internal organs) with bacteriuria (presence of bacteria in the urine)
Comments: Escherichia coli strain F11. This strain was originally isolated from a woman with a case of cystitis (infection of the bladder with no involvement of kidneys or internal organs) with bacteriuria (presence of bacteria in the urine). This stain was supplied by Dr H.L.T. Mobley from the Dept. of Microbiology at the University of Michigan, and is a member of the extra-intestinal pathogenic Eschericha coli group (ExPEC) that produce infections in the kidneys and cerebrospinal fluid. This strain produces a number of virulence factors including serotype O6:H31, mannose-resistant hemagglutinins (MRHA/S, MRHA/H), hemolysin, aerobactin, pap-pili and the PapG III allele (adehsin) and is capable of colonization in mouse models of infection.Genomic sequencing included two libraries - a small insert library (4-5 kb) and a large insert library (10-12 kb) from which 21,037 and 45,464 reads were sequenced, respectively. This amount of sequence represents 10X coverage of the genome. The preliminary assembly is composed of 88 contigs.

Isolation Comments: isolated from a patient with acute pyelonephritis (inflammation of the kidney and pelvis)
Host Health: acute pyelonephritis (inflammation of the kidney and pelvis)
Comments: Escherichia coli strain 536. This strain (536; O6:K15:H31) is a uropathogenic Escherichia coli (UPEC) that was isolated from a patient with acute pyelonephritis (inflammation of the kidney and pelvis). It is a model organism of extraintestinal E. coli, which are among the most common causes of non-hospital-acquired urinary tract infections (UTIs) and UPEC strains are responsible for 40% of nosocomial UTIs. Comparative genomics with other E. coli, especially UPEC strains such as CFT073 will reveal important pathogenicity traits. Studies on strain 536 have revealed at least 5 pathogenicity islands. The project is a collaboration with the group of Prof. Hacker, Institute for Molecular Infection Biology, University of Wurzburg.

Isolation Comments: isolated from a woman with uncomplicated cystitis (bladder inflammation) that has been demonstrated to cause cystitis in a murine urinary tract infection model
Comments: Escherichia coli strain UTI89. This strain (UTI89) is a uropathogenic strain isolated from a woman with uncomplicated cystitis (bladder inflammation) that has been demonstrated to cause cystitis in a murine urinary tract infection model.The genome of UTI89 showed 4 pathogenicity islands. A plasmid was found that was similar to the F plasmid but which also contained virulence genes. Comparison of a set of orthologs from this organism with other E. coli strains showed positive selection on some genes, including those for iron acquisition. Comparison with additional sequences (found in Accession Numbers DQ389000:DQ389068 and DQ440980:DQ441250) of a subset of genes from a number of isolates from patients with UTI infections and isolates from healthy individuals showed positive selection of fepE and amiA genes and some weakly positive selection for ompC.

Isolation Comments: isolated from feces of patient with hemolytic uremic syndrome
Host Health: hemolytic uremic syndrome
Comments: Escherichia coli O157:H7. This strain is associated with Hamburger disease, which is caused by the contamination of meat products by enterohemorrhagic E. coli (EHEC). The identifier O157:H7 refers to the serotype of EHEC, and reflects the specific antigenic markers found on the surface of the cell. EHEC attaches and effaces to cells in the large intestine.There are numerous differences that distinguish O157:H7 from K-12, hundreds of them associated with genomic islands in either strain, including at least 9 large PAIs in O157:H7 that encode virulence factors. A type III secretion system, the locus of enterocyte effacement, numerous toxins and adhesins, as well as fimbrial gene clusters and iron uptake systems are found in these PAIs. Pathogenicity genes are also found on the plasmid pO157.Escherichia coli O157:H7 str. EC508. This strain (ATCC 43889) was isolated from feces of patient with hemolytic uremic syndrome and will be used for comparative analysis
